elements.content: Ten novel metal-organic coordination polymers, [M5(μ3-OH)2(2,3-PDCO)4(H2O)4·xH2O] (2,3-PDCO = pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid N-oxide, M = Mn2+ and x = 3 for 1, M = Co2+ and x = 3 for 3, M = Cd2+ and x = 1.5 for 10), [Mn(2,3-PDCO)(4,4′-bpy)(H2O)2] (2), [M2(2,3-PDCO)2(4,4′-bpy)(H2O)2·xH2O] (M = Co2+ and x = 1 for 4, M = Zn2+ and x = 0 for 7), [M(2,3-PDCO)(L)·H2O] (M = Co2+ and L = bbix (1,4-bis(benzimidazol-1-ylmethyl)-benzene) for 5, M = Zn2+ and L = bix (1,4-bis(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-benzene) for 8), [Cu(2,3-PDCO)(4,4′-bpy)·H2O] (6), [Zn2(2,3-PDCO)2(bbi)] (bbi = 1,1′-(1,4-butanediyl)bis(imidazole)) (9), were obtained under hydrothermal conditions and characterized structurally. The networks exhibit a variety of topologies and coordination modes at the metal centers. 1, 3, and 10 are isostructural and possess three-dimensional (3D) frameworks with penta-nuclear metal clusters as secondary building units (SBU). 5 and 7 individually exhibit a one-dimensional (1D) infinite chain and two-dimensional (2D) rectangular grid architecture with 14-membered metallocycle as SBU. Both 6 and 8 adopt 2D chiral rectangular grid, whereas 2 features a 3D compact framework, all of which contain 1D single-chain SBU. 4 and 9 exhibit 2D brickwalllike layer structure and 2D bilayer framework, respectively, both of which consist of 1D ladderlike chain SBU. To the best of our knowledge, they are the first examples with pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid N-oxide introduced into the coordination polymeric framework. Even if these complexes do not possess any chiral ligand, 6 and 8 have chiral space groups and second-harmonic generation (SHG) responses. The thermal stabilities for 1−10, the photoluminescence properties for 7, 8, 9, and 10, as well as magnetic behaviors for 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6 were examined, and the results indicated that the complexes seem to be good candidates of novel hybrid inorganic−organic photoactive materials with excellent thermal stability, whereas they do not have long-range ordering or other peculiar magnetic phenomena.

Introduction

In recent years, the rational design of novel metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) have attracted great interest from chemists, and considerable efforts have been focused on the design, synthesis, and characterization of novel multidimensional MOFs, not only because of their intriguing variety of architectures and topologies but also because of their tremendous potential applications in the fields of electronic, magnetic, optical, absorbent, and catalytic materials.

elements.content: The organic aromatic polycarboxylate ligands, especially 1,4-benzenedicarboxylate, 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylate, and 1,2,4,5-benzenetetracarboxylate, have been extensively applied in the construction of a rich variety of infinite high-dimensional structures because of their diverse coordination modes and high structural stability. Nevertheless, pyridine dicarboxylic acid N-oxide remains largely unexplored so far. Most recently, we have systematically investigated a series of extended coordination networks constructed from pyridine-2,6-dicarboxylic acid N-oxide(2,6-PDCO) under mild hydrothermal conditions, which display versatile architectures, varying from 1D helix, 2D brick wall and herringbone to 3D interpenetration in the presence of different N-containing auxiliary ligands. As the continuance of this research, we target a new class of high-dimensional coordination polymers built up from pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid N-oxide(2,3-PDCO). The 2,3-PDCO ligand, bearing both carboxylate and N-oxide binding units, with its two carboxylate groups in site 2 and 3, is structurally unsymmetrical and possesses higher dipole moment than 2,6-PDCO. In addition, The N-oxide group of 2,3-PDCO is a far better electron donor than the ring nitrogen atom of pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid (2,3-PDC); the oxygen atom of N-oxide entity potentially could link more than one metal centers compared with nitrogen atom of 2,3-PDC. Therefore, such a ligand may exhibit more rich coordination modes.

Experimental Section

Materials and Measurements

Reagents and solvents employed were commercially available and used as received. 2,3-PDCO, bix, bbix, and bbi were prepared by literature methods. C, H, and N microanalyses were carried out with a Perkin-Elmer 240 elemental analyzer. IR spectra were recorded on KBr discs on a Bruker Vector 22 spectrophotometer in 4000-400 cm-1 region. Fluorescence measurements were recorded with a Hitachi 850 fluorescence spectrophotometer. Thermogravimetric analyses were performed on a simultaneous SDT 2960 thermal analyzer under flowing N2 with a heating rate of 10 °C/min between ambient temperature and 800 °C. A pulsed Q-switched Nd:YAG laser at a wavelength of 1064 nm was used to generate a SHG signal from samples, and the backward scattered SHG light was collected using a spherical concave mirror and passed through a filter which transmits only 532 nm radiations. Magnetic susceptibility on crushed polycrystalline samples were measured over range of 1.8-300 K using a Quantum Design MPMS-5S superconducting quantum interference device (SQUID) magnetometer, and diamagnetic corrections were made using Pascal's constants.

elements.content: In the crystal of 7, Zn(II) ion lies in a distorted tetrahedral coordination sphere (Figure a) defined by two carboxylate oxygen atoms from different 2,3-PDCO ligands, one 4,4′-bpy nitrogen donor and one terminal water molecule. The average Zn−O bond length for the carboxylate groups amounts to 1.933 Å and is slightly shorter than that involving the water molecules (1.982 Å). Two carboxylate groups are close to perpendicular and present dihedral angles of ca. 11 and 82° with the plane of correspondingly linking pyridine ring individually. Additionally, the pair of pyridyl rings in 4,4′-bpy spacers are coplanar. The fully deprotonated 2,3-PDCO2− anions act as bidentate bridging ligands in d-mode linking Zn ions through two monodentate carboxylate moieties (Chart ) with Zn···Zn separations of 4.960 Å to form 14-membered metallocycle being similar to 5. This kind of metallocycles are further interlinked by 4,4′-bpy to generate a 1D chain along the crystallographic [011̅] direction (Figure b). It is noteworthy that the N-oxide moiety (O5) does not participate in coordination to Zn ions, but involves in stronger hydrogen-bond interactions with coordination water (O6) and weaker interactions with C12 atom of 4,4′-bpy, moreover, the uncoordinated carboxylate groups (O2, O4) are hydrogen-bonded to 2,3-PDCO carbon atoms (C5, C7) from adjacent chain. The existences of hydrogen bond interactions further extend 1D chain into 3D framework (see the , Figure S3).

It is worth mentioning here that the N-oxide moiety (O1) and the free water molecules (O6) respectively have weak bonding interactions with Cu1 atom and Cu2 atom at the axial sites (Cu1−O1 2.480(5), Cu2−O6 2.505(5) Å). Two carboxylate groups form dihedral angles of ca. 108 and 137° with the plane of corresponding pyridine ring, and the pair of pyridyl rings in each rigid 4,4′-bpy ligand are significantly twisted, with dihedral angles of 42 and 81°, respectively. A synergistic distortion effect of 2,3-PDCO and 4,4′-bpy ligands leads to the formation of chiral framework.

The most interesting structural feature of 8 is that 1D chains are further connected by flexible bix spacer along b-axis to adopt a 2D chiral puckered rectangular grid architecture with regular parallelogrammic cavities (8.400 × 13.827 Å based on d Zn···Zn) (Figure b). In crystals of both 4 and 9, 2,3-PDCO2− anions bridge metal centers to form 1D ladder-like chains acting as SBU (Chart ), namely, g-PDCO promotes the formation of ladder fragment in the architecture.

In present study, the 2,3-PDCO entities in 1−10 totally adopt seven different coordination modes (Chart ). All carboxyl groups of 2,3-PDCO ligands are deprotonated, which is in agreement with IR spectra analyses (absence of absorption bands ∼1700 cm−1 from −COOH). Of the previously reported coordination polymers, the 2,6-PDCO anions merely display two distinct coordination fashions as illustrated in Chart , which is obviously less in comparison with those of 2,3-PDCO. Unambiguously, the versatile coordination mode of 2,3-PDCO is directly related to the construction of different extended architecture.

Photoluminescence Properties

Because of the higher thermal stability and the ability of affecting the emission wavelength of organic ligands, syntheses of inorganic-organic hybrid materials by the judicious choice of conjugated organic spacers and transition metal centers (especially for d10 systems ) is an effective approach for obtaining new luminescent materials.

elements.content: Emission spectra of 7, 8, 9, and 10 in the solid state are investigated at room temperature. Excitation at 340 nm leads to stronger fluorescent emission bands at 398, 411, and 420 nm for 7; 399, 409, and 418 nm for 9; and 397 nm for 10, whereas weaker fluorescent emission bands are observed at ca. 396, 408, and 417 nm for 8. The fluorescent emissions for 10 probably originate from the formation of Cd5(μ3-OH)2 cluster, which is similar to those of [Cd8(OH)4(H2O)10(na)12] probed by molecular orbital calculations. Despite the different coordination geometries, ligand environments and metal ions, the emission spectra of 7, 8, and 9 resemble to each other, thus, the fluorescent emissions in 7, 8, and 9 are likely ascribed to the π−π* emission within the ligand 2,3-PDCO (these three compounds possess such ligand) even though the free 2,3-PDCO does not exhibit obvious luminescence under the same condition. Recently, the observation of luminescence enhancement of organic ligands in d10 systems have been widely reported, one of the key reasons can be explainable in the fact that a flexible ligand chelating to the metal center lead to enhance its rigidity, which reduces the loss of energy through a radiationless pathway.

Magnetic Properties

To construct novel magnetic porous frameworks with interesting structure topology and improved magnetic properties is rapidly being developed. The motivation in the field is justified by not only the intellectual challenge of understanding the fundamental correlation between structures and magnetic properties, but also the development of new types of functional molecule-based magnetic materials. 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6 possess open shell metal ions, so their magnetic properties were examined.

elements.content: The 3D MOFs of 1 and 3 are constructed from penta-nuclear clusters. If the magnetic interactions between clusters are neglected, the magnetic behavior for both compounds can be described as a penta-nuclear spin system. Based on the magnetic exchange model as shown in Scheme , the spin Hamiltonian can be written below: H = − J 1 S 4 ( S 1 + S 2 + S 3 + S 5 ) − J 2 ( S 1 S 2 + S 3 S 5 ) For both 1 and 3, the expressions for the temperature dependency of magnetic susceptibility deduced from eq are fairly complicated. Fortunately, the magnetic coupling interactions within a penta-nuclear cluster are also weak for both complexes, which variations of χ m −1 versus T exhibit simply Curie−Weiss behavior as shown in Figure . For 1, the fits for χm −1 versus T plot in the range 2−300 K gave C = 4.31(9) emu K mol−1 and θ = −5.26(19) K, which indicates an AFM interaction between Mn(II) ions within a cluster. Field dependence of the magnetization, M, shows a slow increase with a maximum value of 4.58 μB at 7T. In plot of χm −1−T of 3, above 40 K the temperature dependency of χm −1 is almost linear, and a negative Weiss constant θ = −30.8(8) K was derived from the best linear fit of χm −1−T in temperature range 45−300 K, which also indicates an AFM interaction between Co(II) ions within a cluster. In its M−H plot, M shows a slow increase with a maximum value of 1.42 μB at 7T (but does not reach the magnetic saturation).

To date, they are the first examples of coordination polymer system into which pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid N-oxide has been introduced. Ligand 2,3-PDCO, shows exceptional abilities as versatile bridges to link two or more metallic centers (7 kinds of binding modes), which result in the complexity and diversity of the coordination frameworks (such as penta-nuclear metal cluster, 14-membered metallocycle, 1D single-strand chain and 1D ladderlike chain-based MOFs). The present study demonstrates that the ligand natures (flexibility/rigidity), coordination geometric needs of metal together with weakly intermolecular interactions, such as hydrogen bond interactions, cooperated affect the formation of the supramolecular architecture, and finally control the crystal packing of MOFs. Crystals of both 6 and 8 have chiral space group and second-harmonic generation (SHG) responses even if no organic ligand possesses chirality; 7, 8, 9, and 10 appear to be good candidates of novel hybrid inorganic−organic photoactive materials with high thermal stability.

Conclusion

In summary, we successfully synthesized ten novel coordination polymers with different architectures, which were constructed from 2,3-PDCO, in the presence of different N-heterocycles used as spacers under similar hydrothermal conditions. To date, they are the first examples of coordination polymer system into which pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid N-oxide has been introduced. Ligand 2,3-PDCO, shows exceptional abilities as versatile bridges to link two or more metallic centers (7 kinds of binding modes), which result in the complexity and diversity of the coordination frameworks (such as penta-nuclear metal cluster, 14-membered metallocycle, 1D single-strand chain and 1D ladderlike chain-based MOFs). The present study demonstrates that the ligand natures (flexibility/rigidity), coordination geometric needs of metal together with weakly intermolecular interactions, such as hydrogen bond interactions, cooperated affect the formation of the supramolecular architecture, and finally control the crystal packing of MOFs. Crystals of both 6 and 8 have chiral space group and second-harmonic generation (SHG) responses even if no organic ligand possesses chirality; 7, 8, 9, and 10 appear to be good candidates of novel hybrid inorganic-organic photoactive materials with high thermal stability.
